(In the description of Tartarus (548-561), note the many allitera- tions, with the picturesque use of certain consonants‚ especially s, r, t (cf. 548, 550, 551, 554, 557, 558, 559, 560, 561). In the Sibyl's narrative of horrors. Virgil exhibits a wonderful resourcefulness in linguistic effects. Alliteration, onomatopoeia, and *figures of rhetoric are numerous. Hard and harsh consonants (t, p, c, s, r) again abound. See 570, 571, 572, 573, 574, 577, 578, 580, 583, 591, 592 f„ 602, 609, 611, 616, 627. For vowel effects‚ see especially 572, 576.
